ocr.line: etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν
ocr.sentence: etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

De Or. 39. μεγάλη τε τῶν πλανῶνται καὶ δέρκεσσι. πολύτροπον καλῶς πλανῶνται, Plut. s. Demetr. πολύτροπον καλῶς τὴν πλανῶνται καλῶς σκυτίζειν. Schol. ad Eur. Tro. IV. 247. Theophrast. s. De Audiend. c. 25. ὅτε δ᾽ οἱ διὰ περιστρέψαι τὰ τῶν ἐν αὐτοῖς μισουργημένα κατηνοιγμένα, ποιοίμαι τὸ μετὰ σκυτήματος τὸ τῶν πλανῶνται κρίσιμον ἀγῶνα. V. 26. σκυτίζουσι. καὶ τοὺς κελάδηνας ἐκλαμβάνουσι, Plut. s. Demetr. e. καὶ τοὺς εὔριπτους πολλοὺς ἐκλαμβάνουσι καὶ τοὺς κελάδηνας. T. IV. De. Gym. p. 1263. I τὰ κελάδηνα κρυπτὸν ἀγῶνα, eo quod quisque in ea locorum τὸν τρόπον. c. 17. παρὰ τοῦ κελάδηνος, eo quod καλως καὶ πρὸς ἀρετὴν καλῶς. ad Hipp. p. 678. κλιμακὴν ἐκλαμβάνειν καλῶς ἀκριβῶς καλῶς σκυτίζειν, ib. 549. ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται τὰ χρῶμα κρίνεσθαι, κ. τ. λ. c. 583. eo quod quisque in eis τὴν κριτικὴν μορίαν. πρὸς κελάδην, ib. 479. κρίται κελάδηνα καλῶς ποιεῖσθαι τοὺς πλανῶνται, Plato, Legg. V. 913. De Rep. IV. 418. A. V. 32. τὸν κλίμακα τοῦ ποιούμενος περι κελάδην ἑλεσθαι, Aristotelis Top. 7. τὴν ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται τὴν προσωπικὴν γλῶσσαν ἔχειν καλῶς ποιεῖσθαι. ἀπαρταγμένα, καλῶς καὶ ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται εὐλεγέσθαι. πλάνους δὲ τὰς ἐκλεκτὰς κείμεναι τὰς δεινα

ocr.line: lsaeus Cir. p. 69. §. 11. μὴ θέλοι Lycurg. Leocr. p. 157, 77.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

I τὰ κελάδηνα κρυπτὸν ἀγῶνα, eo quod quisque in ea locorum τὸν τρόπον. c. 17. παρὰ τοῦ κελάδηνος, eo quod καλως καὶ πρὸς ἀρετὴν καλῶς. ad Hipp. p. 678. κλιμακὴν ἐκλαμβάνειν καλῶς ἀκριβῶς καλῶς σκυτίζειν, ib. 549. ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται τὰ χρῶμα κρίνεσθαι, κ. τ. λ. c. 583. eo quod quisque in eis τὴν κριτικὴν μορίαν. πρὸς κελάδην, ib. 479. κρίται κελάδηνα καλῶς ποιεῖσθαι τοὺς πλανῶνται, Plato, Legg. V. 913. De Rep. IV. 418. A. V. 32. τὸν κλίμακα τοῦ ποιούμενος περι κελάδην ἑλεσθαι, Aristotelis Top. 7. τὴν ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται τὴν προσωπικὴν γλῶσσαν ἔχειν καλῶς ποιεῖσθαι. ἀπαρταγμένα, καλῶς καὶ ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται εὐλεγέσθαι. πλάνους δὲ τὰς ἐκλεκτὰς κείμεναι τὰς δεινα

ocr.line: tur. Rectius Schol. Rom. τοῖς ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο,
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

I. 6. καλὸν τὸ πλανῶντα καὶ ἁλῶν καλον καὶ σειρὰν. ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται καλοί καὶ ἱμῆναι. ἀποστεῖλαι τοὺς ἐν τῷ πλανῶνται καὶ κελάδηναι, Theophrast. s. De Or. 39. μεγάλη τε τῶν πλανῶνται καὶ δέρκεσσι. πολύτροπον καλῶς πλανῶνται, Plut. s. Demetr. πολύτροπον καλῶς τὴν πλανῶνται καλῶς σκυτίζειν. Schol. ad Eur. Tro. IV. 247. Theophrast. s. De Audiend. c. 25. ὅτε δ᾽ οἱ διὰ περιστρέψαι τὰ τῶν ἐν αὐτοῖς μισουργημένα κατηνοιγμένα, ποιοίμαι τὸ μετὰ σκυτήματος τὸ τῶν πλανῶνται κρίσιμον ἀγῶνα. V. 26. σκυτίζουσι. καὶ τοὺς κελάδηνας ἐκλαμβάνουσι, Plut. s. Demetr. e. καὶ τοὺς εὔριπτους πολλοὺς ἐκλαμβάνουσι καὶ τοὺς κελάδηνας. T. IV. De. Gym. p. 1263. I τὰ κελάδηνα κρυπτὸν ἀγῶνα, eo quod quisque in ea locorum τὸν τρόπον. c. 17. παρὰ τοῦ κελάδηνος, eo quod καλως καὶ πρὸς ἀρετὴν καλῶς. ad Hipp. p. 678. κλιμακὴν ἐκλαμβάνειν καλῶς ἀκριβῶς καλῶς σκυτίζειν, ib. 549. ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται τὰ χρῶμα κρίνεσθαι, κ. τ. λ. c. 583. eo quod quisque in eis τὴν κριτικὴν μορίαν. πρὸς κελάδην, ib. 479. κρίται κελάδηνα καλῶς ποιεῖσθαι τοὺς πλανῶνται, Plato, Legg. V. 913. De Rep. IV. 418. A. V. 32. τὸν κλίμακα τοῦ ποιούμενος περι κελάδην ἑλεσθαι, Aristotelis Top. 7. τὴν ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται τὴν προσωπικὴν γλῶσσαν ἔχειν καλῶς ποιεῖσθαι. ἀπαρταγμένα, καλῶς καὶ ἐν τοῖς πλανῶνται εὐλεγέσθαι. πλάνους δὲ τὰς ἐκλεκτὰς κείμεναι τὰς δεινα

Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. ocr.region: the fiery man. Essay on L. §9. P. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endared.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a commenut on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

prediction.sentence: The man was fiery. He set fire to
prediction.region: 229. ἐπιμέγεν] The word ‘appears’ would be better in our Eng. version. 231. ἀρρείως] ‘Vainly’ (see supr. 117; Hesych. ἀρριαις), but perhaps here ‘doubtfully,’ because he has little experience of the nature of men. The text should be supplied by τοσοῦτον ἂν ἐπερίσεσθαι δύνασθαί, which has MS. authority. The sense is not in the least altered. 232. ἔπερνα] A word used in the Ion. poets and by the Attic writers for the ‘pasture’ of a sheep, but, with the idea of ‘grazing,’ is never used in the Doric dialect (cf. Plu., De septem, 28; Hesych., ἐπερνη μη τυμενῆ, 358; κλισία το ἐπερνη, 253; &c.). See K. W. 591. 233. γλώσσαι λαμπροί] A word which occurs again in 237, and is connected with the γλῶττα of the next verse, where the contrast of the inanimate and animate is expressed by οὐ παλαιέτοις. 241. καίπερ] ‘Though they may be, in fact, only a set of common sailors.’ In the text καὶ is to be supplied, with the omission of μὴ, and the words (as in supr. 238) should be joined. 246. καθαρίζειν] is here, like κοινως, a substantive used adverbially

These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ μέγας μῦθος] ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, ὦ μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in general. ἀέξει] Not ‘exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

487. πρὸς τὰ χρόνα] ‘In the long run.’
Tecmessa: I am not, Ajax, of those whose counsels are given up to the winds.
I hear thee, daughter, in the dark,
The sound of thy voice alone of those that are
Mine,—and I answer thee.
What have I said
That thou dost frown at me, thou who hast made
My house thy dwelling, and hast taken me,
Born free, for wife, and hast made a slave
Of that which the Elysian fates gave thee?
How is the speech, I pray thee, of thy lord?
Is he in safety? Is his mind in peace?
For me to tell my thoughts to thee, how they
Are set, and how my heart is urging them?
For I see that thou dost hold me not so dear
As once was thy wont. Thou dost keep me not
From the eyes of the Greeks; nor hast thou won
Fame for thyself by saving me, nor art
Thou now more tender to me than before.
It is not for my sake that thou dost love me;
But thou hast some other purpose in thy mind.
I see the truth,—not to thy honour,
But to mine own destruction and thine own.
Thou dost not mean that my life should be
In safety and ease, where thou dost lodge,
As thou hast spoken.
I do not know
What the gods may have in store for me; but this
Thy thought is,—to bring a son to be the heir
Of thy estate, by me.
I see thy face,
And the words that thou dost utter. Do I not
Remember that I am a woman, and know
How these thy words sound?
There is no need,
Much more, to tell of my thoughts, how they
Are fixed, and how my heart urges them on.
For it is plain to me, how thou dost love me,
Not for my own sake, but for that thou dost
Have

Tecmessa: I am not, Ajax, of those whose counsels are given up to the winds.
I hear thee, daughter, in the dark,
The sound of thy voice alone of those that are
Mine,—and I answer thee.
What have I said
That thou dost frown at me, thou who hast made
My house thy dwelling, and hast taken me,
Born free, for wife, and hast made a slave
Of that which the Elysian fates gave thee?
How is the speech, I pray thee, of thy lord?
Is he in safety? Is his mind in peace?
For me to tell my thoughts to thee, how they
Are set, and how my heart is urging them?
For I see that thou dost hold me not so dear
As once was thy wont. Thou dost keep me not
From the eyes of the Greeks; nor hast thou won
Fame for thyself by saving me, nor art
Thou now more tender to me than before.
It is not for my sake that thou dost love me;
But thou hast some other purpose in thy mind.
I see the truth,—not to thy honour,
But to mine own destruction and thine own.
Thou dost not mean that my life should be
In safety and ease, where thou dost lodge,
As thou hast spoken.
I do not know
What the gods may have in store for me; but this
Thy thought is,—to bring a son to be the heir
Of thy estate, by me.
I see thy face,
And the words that thou dost utter. Do I not
Remember that I am a woman, and know
How these thy words sound?
There is no need,
Much more, to tell of my thoughts, how they

For it is plain to me, how thou dost love me,
Not for my own sake, but for that thou dost

487. πρὸς τὰ χρόνα] ‘In the long run.’
Tecmessa: I am not, Ajax, of those whose counsels are given up to the winds.
I hear thee, daughter, in the dark,
The sound of thy voice alone of those that are
Mine,—and I answer thee.
What have I said
That thou dost frown at me, thou who hast made
My house thy dwelling, and hast taken me,
Born free, for wife, and hast made a slave
Of that which the Elysian fates gave thee?
How is the speech, I pray thee, of thy lord?
Is he in safety? Is his mind in peace?
For me to tell my thoughts to thee, how they
Are set, and how my heart is urging them?
For I see that thou dost hold me not so dear
As once was thy wont. Thou dost keep me not
From the eyes of the Greeks; nor hast thou won
Fame for thyself by saving me, nor art
Thou now more tender to me than before.
It is not for my sake that thou dost love me;
But thou hast some other purpose in thy mind.
I see the truth,—not to thy honour,
But to mine own destruction and thine own.
Thou dost not mean that my life should be
In safety and ease, where thou dost lodge,
As thou hast spoken.
I do not know
What the gods may have in store for me; but this
Thy thought is,—to bring a son to be the heir
Of thy estate, by me.
I see thy face,
And the words that thou dost utter. Do I not
Remember that I am a woman, and know
How these thy words sound?
There is no need,
Much more, to tell of my thoughts, how they
Are fixed, and how my heart urges them on.
For it is plain to me, how thou dost love me,
Not for my own sake, but for that thou dost

487. πρὸς τὰ χρόνα] ‘In the long run.’
Tecmessa: I am not, Ajax, of those whose counsels are given up to the winds.
I hear thee, daughter, in the dark,
The sound of thy voice alone of those that are
Mine,—and I answer thee.
What have I said
That thou dost frown at me, thou who hast made
My house thy dwelling, and hast taken me,
Born free, for wife, and hast made a slave
Of that which the Elysian fates gave thee?
How is the speech, I pray thee, of thy lord?
Is he in safety? Is his mind in peace?
For me to tell my thoughts to thee, how they
Are set, and how my heart is urging them?
For I see that thou dost hold me not so dear
As once was thy wont. Thou dost keep me not
From the eyes of the Greeks; nor hast thou won
Fame for thyself by saving me, nor art
Thou now more tender to me than before.
It is not for my sake that thou dost love me;
But thou hast some other purpose in thy mind.
I see the truth,—not to thy honour,
But to mine own destruction and thine own.
Thou dost not mean that my life should be
In safety and ease, where thou dost lodge,
As thou hast spoken.
I do not know
What the gods may have in store for me; but this
Thy thought is,—to bring a son to be the heir
Of thy estate, by me.
I see thy face,
And the words that thou dost utter. Do I not
Remember that I am a woman, and know
How these thy words sound?
There is no need,
Much more, to tell of my thoughts, how they
Are fixed, and how my heart urges them on.
For it is plain to me, how thou dost love me,
Not for my own sake, but for that thou dost

For the poetical plural, ‘outbursts of wrath.’ cp. Trach. 882, rtves νόσοι; and see Essay on L. § 20. p. 30. The plural of θυμός occurs in Plat. Phil. 40 E: Legg. 11. 034 A, 6 δὲ .. ἐν φόβοις δειλίας, 5 τῖσιν ἐπιθυμίαις ἢ φθόνοις Gupols δυ- σιάτοις γιγνόμενος. (νεικεῶν.) 719 foll. The proscenium has been vacant during the preceding ode. A single figure is now seen approaching from the opposite direction to that in which Ajax went forth. The man proves to be Teucer’s forerunner. ñ The effect of the following scene is twofold. On the one hand, the Chorus and Tecmessa are roused from their security, and go anxiously in search of

prediction.region: the fugitive, whose safety is of such vital importance to the fortunes of Greece. On the other hand, the spectators are left in a position where the future is shrouded in impenetrable gloom. Their anxiety is, indeed, relieved by the appearance of the aged Medeia, whose presence is a pledge that Teucer will not fail to return. But the sight of the heroine of the piece is scarcely sufficient to dissipate the feeling of foreboding caused by the death of Aias, which is now no longer avoidable, and which is to be followed by the catastrophe of the piece itself. groundtruth.region: Il. I. 213 τρὶς τόσσα.. δῶρα: Eur. El. 1092 δὶς τόσως (‘in double measure’).- ἐξ ἁπλῶν: Tr. 619 (χάρις) ἐξ ἁπλῆς διπλῆ. 278 ff. δέδοικα μὴ.. ἥκῃ. Though ἥκει is tenable (‘I fear that it certainly has come’ ), ἥκῃ seems better, since there is still a real uncertainty and anxiety in their minds. See on El. 580. (ἥκοι, which was the common reading, is of course impossible here.) πῶς γάρ, sc. ἄλλῶς ἔχει; Normally, πῶς γάρ follows a negative statement, as in El. 911 οὐδ’ αὖ σύ· πῶς γάρ; (sc. ἔδρασας): while πῶς γὰρ οὔ follows an affirmative, as ib. 1307 οἶσθα μὲν τἀν- θένδε, πῶς γὰρ οὔ; The use of πῶς γάρ here is thus peculiar, though the sense is clear. εἰ πεπαυμένος κ.τ.λ. The fact that despair has succeeded to frenzy argues that he is under the spell of some angry god. When the malady passed away, his mind ought to have recovered a healthy tone. They had already hinted at a θεία νόσος as a possibility (186). μηδέν τι: Eur. groundtruth.region: Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. ocr.region: κἀπ’ dpol: for this modest καί, cp. Ph. 192 εἴπερ κἀγώ τι φρονῶ, and n. on Ant. 719. Repar should naturally go with κἀπ’ ἐμοί, though βλέπειν ἐπί τινι seems to occur nowhere else, and ἐπιβλέπειν τινί only in Lucian Astr. 20 καὶ σφίσι γνομένοισι τῷ μὲν ἡ Ἀφροδίτη τῷ δὲ ὁ Ζεὺς... ἐπέβλεψαν (‘loocked with favour’). The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). Ajax, sitting among his victims, and meditating his own destruction, was the subject of a famous picture by Timomachus of Byzantium. Philostratus ( Vit. Apoll. 2. 22 § 5) thus describes it: rov Alavra. τὸν Τιμομάχου. . dwexrovbra τἀν τῇ Τροίᾳ βουκόλια καθῆσθαι ἀπειρηκότα [cp. ν. 325 ἤσυχος θακεῖ], βουλὴν ποιούμενον καὶ

ocr.sentence: 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere.
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

prediction.region: cc. of a transitive verb. 6544 σεμορόν. This word is used only by Homer for the couch in which the corpse is laid. In the case before us the expression σεμορομένοις πεπλοῖς λέγεται may perhaps be compared to νεφελοφόροις (Il. 2. 610). The plural in 671 is either a plural of respect, or a plural of the object. In the former sense it would mean ‘favouring the man who is to bear the child.’ In the latter sense, it would mean ‘which he should receive for his wife’s sake’; i. e., for bringing the child up. The use of the plural of respect is favoured by the fact that in 677 τῶν σεμορωμένων παιδικῶν γενεαίων is used for ‘the ages of boys.’ For the word παιδικὸς cp. Ph. 1047 τοὺς ἀρχαῖους παιδικοὺς γενεαίους. The use of the plural object is confirmed by ἑρπετὰς δὲ ἔχουσαν (943). In the last clause περίτραπον is properly an attributive, but it has also, in the genitive, the sense ‘by which the child is born.’—τετράγων. The word is a compound of τέτρα and χώγω. Cp. Eustath. on Il. 8. 419. 6571. A different reading: ἵνα μετὰ κατεκτούντων αὐτόν ἐξ ὀπίσω θοῤῥῆσκε. If the first τὰ is retained, the verb is to be taken intransitively, and the phrase would mean, ‘in such a position that I shall see him when I arrive.’ The best reading is τὰ δὲ θοῤῥῆσκε with τὰ ἐξ ὀπίσω as in Il. 3. 330, where the object-acc. occurs. In the last clause θαλὰμ would be best translated ‘bed

prediction.region: cc. of a transitive verb. 6544 σεμορόν. This word is used only by Homer for the couch in which the corpse is laid. In the case before us the expression σεμορομένοις πεπλοῖς λέγεται may perhaps be compared to νεφελοφόροις (Il. 2. 610). The plural in 671 is either a plural of respect, or a plural of the object. In the former sense it would mean ‘favouring the man who is to bear the child.’ In the latter sense, it would mean ‘which he should receive for his wife’s sake’; i. e., for bringing the child up. The use of the plural of respect is favoured by the fact that in 677 τῶν σεμορωμένων παιδικῶν γενεαίων is used for ‘the ages of boys.’ For the word παιδικὸς cp. Ph. 1047 τοὺς ἀρχαῖους παιδικοὺς γενεαίους. The use of the plural object is confirmed by ἑρπετὰς δὲ ἔχουσαν (943). In the last clause περίτραπον is properly an attributive, but it has also, in the genitive, the sense ‘by which the child is born.’—τετράγων. The word is a compound of τέτρα and χώγω. Cp. Eustath. on Il. 8. 419. 6571. A different reading: ἵνα μετὰ κατεκτούντων αὐτόν ἐξ ὀπίσω θοῤῥῆσκε. If the first τὰ is retained, the verb is to be taken intransitively, and the phrase would mean, ‘in such a position that I shall see him when I arrive.’ The best reading is τὰ δὲ θοῤῥῆσκε with τὰ ἐξ ὀπίσω as in Il. 3. 330, where the object-acc. occurs. In the last clause θαλὰμ would be best translated ‘bed

Hier iſt das Adverb zu ἠπείθεια (die Überredung 19/3) (Ein. von εἰθισμένος, vgl. 465; 575; 641). 20. τέρσεται (τερσέω) die Stelle von βαστάζειν, welches (in dem Sinne von Odyss. € 220) εἰρηνεία αἰδοίησις τότε διαλήθῃ μηδέτερ. (Kr. II 8, 10). — Ἕρης (ἥρως) iſt hier mit einem Adjektiv, das διὰ (μετέπειτα) fehlt (πρὸς γὰρ τὴν εὐθύνην καλέει). Vgl. Eum. 571; 573. — τίς δ’ (ὅ) ist die Indikativform der Interrogation (vgl. 155). — δαίμων αὐτὸς iſt in diesem ὅρασις der Schauplatz.
4. οὔτ’ ἄλλον τινα, ἀλλὰ πολλά τε καὶ κρινόντα κάρια. — ἕστηκε τε σὺν ἐμῇ τῇ μάντῃ καὶ σκέφθει τι τὸν τρόπον. — ἐκπίπτει iſt hier nicht den Wunsch nach der Ausführung ausdrücken, sondern den Wunsch nach dem σχέσιν (vgl. 247); vgl. 766. — πρὸς ἐμὸν χάριν ἑνός (κατ’ ἀντίτυπον; vgl. 632; 641) iſt für εἰ ὡς ὅτι πολλὰ μὲν καὶ κρινόντα κάρια σὺν ἐμῇ τῇ μάντῃ ἕστηκες, ἀλλὰ καὶ σκέφθει τι τὸν τρόπον. εἰ ὅτι ἕστηκες ist eine κατ’ ἀντίτυπον, vgl. 410.
5. οἱ δὲ ἀμφοτέρων νοστίμων ἄνδρες καὶ τραχέων ἴσαι ἦσαν. ἥκων ὡς λυμῆς μέγας τραχεῖος, καὶ μέγα νοστήματος, ὡς φρένας καὶ σώματα δι’ αὐτὰς καθαρὸς καὶ ἦτε δε

Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraut. — μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant.675f. 1081f. 670v .. ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. — δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν re vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (ris) Kr. 1 8 64, 4,5. — zao07: zu 496. 1083. Es findet fih 85 ovoim» (πνευμάτων) Dew, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobe). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). — πεσεῖν das Futurum wird Durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter“) vertreten. 1084. xai δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. — καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein- ſtellend, heilſam. — Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 920 ἔσθ’ ὅπου To δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ oreveı. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. 1846, 6,9, Cu. 8 153, 3, Kr. 8 83, Ku. 825, 3. — Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ oe Vapo, x0V ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν do’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

groundtruth.region: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα δ. i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und ſcheut, vor Augen ſteht.- Der Schol. führt einen Spruch des Epicharm an: ἔνθα δέος, ἐνταῦθα καὶ αἰδώς. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant. 675 f. 1081 f, ὅπου . . ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν τε vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (τίς) Kr. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.
